  "prompt": "What is the main function of the brachiocephalic artery?",
  "response": "The brachiocephalic artery (also called the innominate artery) is a major blood vessel that branches off from the aortic arch. Its main function is to supply oxygenated blood to the right side of the head, neck, and right upper limb. Specifically, it divides into two branches:\n\n1. Right common carotid artery: Supplies blood to the right side of the head and neck\n2. Right subclavian artery: Provides blood to the right upper limb and right shoulder region\n\nThe brachiocephalic artery plays a crucial role in distributing blood from the heart to important regions of the upper body, ensuring proper oxygen and nutrient delivery to these vital areas.",
